<br>
The attack rating and level of your foe contribute heavily to what your AC would 'cap' at in order to diminish in return.<br>
<br>
Example:<br>
<br>
My level 60 warrior now has an unbuffed 1288 AC with max AC gear (got my Kael BP last night).  I'm not sure what it will be buffed, probably in the 1380-1400 range.  When fighting a low 50's foe the attack rating combined with my level advantage should mean that my AC has been soft-capped without even bothering to buff.<br>
<br>
However, every point of AC I can muster above 1288 when tanking something 61+ would still be of use.  At 60 I pretty much only play my warrior for &quot;end-game&quot; encounters, so AC, resists, HP's, haste, and attack are what I try to raise in my equipment and buffs.<br>
<br>
There's more to it than that, but think along those terms and you'll understand the basics.  <br>
<br>
Also note that your chance of resisting an &quot;end-game&quot; dragon's spell or breath would never be above a certain percentage for the sake of the difficulty of the encounter.  This is partially why people swear that going above xxx resist will actually hurt.  It might be capped or simply not that effective after a point, but I sincerely doubt that it rolls over.<br>
 <p>DragonLord Ariakis<BR>
